Brown, conic to convex to plane caps with small knob on disc. Cap orbicular, and hygrophanus, with color changes lighter from the margin to darker on the disc. Gills were brown, attached, and subdistant. Stipe centrally attached , terrete, and equal. Stipe was hollow and brittle. No partial veil. found scattered to gregarious in grass. The few spores I obtained were brown. the three bottom photos are at 400x, and each line is approx. 2.4u

Pileus-Convex to Plano-convex, 3.0-6.0 cm, rugose, disc tawny brown, and pinkish buff or cream toward margin.

Odor- mild, slightly alkaline or raphanoid.
Taste- mild, acidulous or slightly bitter.
Spore Print- White

Microscopic features:
Strongly dextrinoid tramal hyphae, becoming vinaceous red in Melzer’s
Pileipellis- hymeniform, composed of cylindric, clavate, broadly clavate, vesiculose cells 11-38 X 6-20 microns.
Caulocystidia- absent .
Spores- 6.0-9.0 X 3.0-4.5 microns, narrowly elliptical to subcylindrical, slightly inequilateral in profile, hyaline, inamyloid, smooth.
Pleurocystidia- abundant, fusoid or ventricose, inamyloid, refractive, 45-60 × 7-10.0 microns.
Clamps- present

Ok, I have no information to go with here other than the locale, environment, and photography. These were found in a landscaped area at Nasa’s Visitor Center, Titusville Florida, near the Rocket Garden. :) The “groundskeeper” was working near me so I was in no way about to attempt to remove these so I just “tipped” them over and shot some pictures. They were quite large compared to what I usually come across in Pennsylvania, so as a reference I used a lighter to display size as best as I could. I do recall them being “rubbery” to the touch."

I knew the genus from Australia and after a little research, I’m quite confident it is Cymatoderma caperata. It has been reportedly (is that a word?) found in Florida before.
